First, we need to calculate the energy of a single photon. The values of $h$ and $c$ are $6.626 \times 10^{-34} \mathrm{~J~s}$ and $3.00 \times 10^8 \mathrm{~m/s}$, respectively. The wavelength $\lambda = 300 \mathrm{~nm} = 300 \times 10^{-9} \mathrm{~m}$. So, $E = \frac{(6.626 \times 10^{-34} \mathrm{~J~s}) \times (3.00 \times 10^8 \mathrm{~m/s})}{300 \times 10^{-9} \mathrm{~m}}$.

## Step 4: Perform the calculation of the energy of a single photon.
$E = \frac{(6.626 \times 10^{-34}) \times (3.00 \times 10^8)}{300 \times 10^{-9}} = \frac{19.878 \times 10^{-26}}{300 \times 10^{-9}} = 6.626 \times 10^{-19} \mathrm{~J}$.

## Step 5: Calculate the energy of one mole of photons.
To find the energy of one mole of photons, we multiply the energy of a single photon by Avogadro's number ($6.022 \times 10^{23} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}$). So, the energy per mole $= (6.626 \times 10^{-19} \mathrm{~J}) \times (6.022 \times 10^{23} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1})$.

## Step 6: Perform the calculation of the energy of one mole of photons.
Energy per mole $= (6.626 \times 10^{-19}) \times (6.022 \times 10^{23}) = 3.990 \times 10^5 \mathrm{~J/mol}$.

## Step 7: Convert the energy from Joules per mole to kiloJoules per mole.
To convert $\mathrm{J/mol}$ to $\mathrm{kJ/mol}$, we divide by $1000$ since $1 \mathrm{~kJ} = 1000 \mathrm{~J}$. So, $\frac{3.990 \times 10^5}{1000} = 399 \mathrm{~kJ/mol}$.

## Step 8: Compare the calculated energy with the given single-bond energy.
The energy of one mole of UV photons is $399 \mathrm{~kJ/mol}$, which is very close to the typical single-bond energy of $400 \mathrm{~kJ/mol}$.

The final answer is 399.
